AI Marketing Guide

Your complete guide to AI-powered marketing at TaylorMade

Four AI Tools. One Marketing Team.

TaylorMade's marketing team has access to the most capable AI assistants available today. This guide shows you exactly what each tool can do, when to use it, and how to get the best results for your marketing work.

Microsoft Copilot Chat

Your everyday AI assistantâ€”available to all employees

What Is It?

Microsoft Copilot Chat (formerly "free Copilot") is a web-based AI assistant available to everyone at TaylorMade. It's powered by GPT models with web search, includes 15 AI image generations per day, and has Enterprise Data Protection. Access at m365.cloud.microsoft with your @taylormadegolf.com account.

What It Can Do

Web Research
Search the web in real-time with Bing. Get current info with cited sources.
Brainstorming
Generate campaign ideas, taglines, content angles for early ideation.
Image Generation
Create images with DALL-E 3. Limited to 15/day for concepts.
Copilot Pages
Turn conversations into editable documents to share with teammates.
File Upload
Upload documents for analysis and summarization in your session.
Enterprise Protection
Your prompts and data are not used to train AI models.
Critical Limitation

Copilot Chat cannot access your organizational dataâ€”no emails, SharePoint files, meeting transcripts, or company documents. It only searches the public web. For org data access, you need Microsoft 365 Copilot.

Marketing Use Cases

Search for competitor announcements, product launches, and marketing campaigns.

Example
Search for Callaway's latest marketing campaigns from the past 3 months. Summarize their messaging themes, key products featured, and channels used. What can we learn?

Generate ideas for blog posts, social content, email campaigns.

Example
Give me 10 blog post ideas for TaylorMade targeting amateur golfers who want to hit longer drives. Include a mix of educational content, equipment guides, and tips.

Microsoft 365 Copilot

Full AI integration with Office appsâ€”requires license

The Key Differentiator: Organizational Data

M365 Copilot connects to Microsoft Graphâ€”it can access your emails, files, meetings, and organizational data. It's embedded directly in Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Outlook, and Teams. This is what makes it worth $30/user/month for heavy Office users.

Capabilities by App

Copilot in Word

  • Draft with references: "Write a brief using the brand guidelines in SharePoint"
  • Rewrite content: Change tone, length, or style
  • Summarize: Turn long reports into executive summaries
  • Agent Mode: Multi-step document creation with iterative refinement
Example
Draft a 1,000-word blog post about our new Qi35 driver technology. Reference the product spec sheet in SharePoint and match the tone of our existing blog content.

Copilot in Excel

  • Data analysis: "What trends do you see in this campaign data?"
  • Formula creation: "Create a formula to calculate YoY growth"
  • Visualizations: "Create a chart showing performance by channel"
Example
Analyze this campaign data. Which channels drove the highest ROI? Create a summary table showing spend, conversions, and ROAS by channel.

Copilot in PowerPoint

  • Create from files: "Create a presentation from this Word doc"
  • Build from scratch: "Create a 10-slide campaign proposal"
  • Speaker notes: Auto-generate notes for each slide
Example
Create a 12-slide quarterly marketing review. Include: performance highlights, channel breakdown, campaign results, competitive landscape, next quarter priorities.

Copilot in Outlook

  • Draft replies: "Write a polite follow-up asking for their decision"
  • Summarize threads: "What's the key ask in this email chain?"
  • Adjust tone: "Make this more formal"
Example
Draft a follow-up email to the creative agency about campaign assets. Reference my previous email from last week and ask for an updated timeline.

Copilot in Teams

  • Meeting summaries: Real-time and post-meeting recaps
  • Action items: Automatically extract and assign tasks
  • Chat catch-up: Summarize up to 30 days of channel history
Example
What were the key decisions and action items from today's campaign planning meeting? Who was assigned what?

Request a License

To request M365 Copilot access, email it@taylormadegolf.com with your manager approval and business justification. Licenses are allocated based on role requirements and heavy Office app usage.

Claude AI

Superior writing quality for marketing excellence

Why Claude for Marketing?

Claude is the preferred AI for long-form content and nuanced marketing writing. Its 200,000+ token context window processes entire brand guides, campaign histories, and competitive research in one conversation. Writing quality consistently requires less editing than other AI assistants.

Marketing Prompts

Blog Post
Write a 1,500-word blog post titled "The Science of Forgiveness: How the Qi35 Keeps Your Misses in Play" The article should: - Open with a relatable scenario about off-center hits - Explain MOI and CG placement in accessible terms - Reference specific Qi35 technologies (Infinite Carbon Crown, Speed Pocket) - End with a call to get fitted Target: Serious amateur golfers (15-25 handicap). Maintain TaylorMade's confident, innovative voice.
Brief as Word Doc
Create a comprehensive creative brief for our summer golf ball campaign as a Word document: 1. Campaign Overview (name options, duration, budget) 2. Objectives (goals, KPIs) 3. Target Audience (segments, psychographics) 4. Key Messages (primary message, proof points) 5. Creative Direction (tone, visual territory) 6. Channel Plan (priority channels, content needs) 7. Timeline (milestones, deadlines) Create as downloadable .docx file.
Competitor Research
Analyze Titleist's current marketing approach for their TSR driver line: 1. Messaging & Positioning - Key claims, target audience, differentiation 2. Channel Strategy - Most active channels, content types 3. Strengths & Weaknesses - What works, where are gaps? 4. Implications for TaylorMade - Opportunities to differentiate Include sources for all claims.
Pro Tip: Project + Style

Create a Project with brand guidelines uploaded, then apply your Custom Style. Every conversation in that Project will have full brand context and voice consistency built in.

When to Use Each Tool

Use Copilot Chat When...

  • Quick web research or competitive intelligence
  • Brainstorming ideas or generating concepts
  • Creating rough concept images (15/day limit)
  • You don't need organizational data access

Use M365 Copilot When...

  • Working within Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Outlook, or Teams
  • You need to reference emails, files, or meeting transcripts
  • Creating presentations from existing documents
  • Summarizing meetings or long email threads

Use Claude When...

  • Writing long-form content (blogs, whitepapers, case studies)
  • Brand voice consistency is critical
  • Processing large documents (brand guides, research)
  • Quality mattersâ€”content will be published

Use Gemini + Nano Banana When...

  • Creating or editing images for campaigns
  • Need text rendered accurately in images
  • Analyzing video content or multimodal assets
  • Character consistency across multiple images

Prompt Templates

Copy-ready prompts for common marketing tasks

Content Creation

Blog Post TemplateClaude
Write a [WORD COUNT]-word blog post titled "[TITLE]" The article should: - Open with [HOOK TYPE: relatable scenario / surprising stat / question] - Cover these key points: [POINT 1], [POINT 2], [POINT 3] - Reference specific TaylorMade technologies where relevant - End with [CTA: call to action] Target audience: [AUDIENCE DESCRIPTION] Tone: Confident, innovative, authentic to TaylorMade voice
Product DescriptionClaude
Write product descriptions for [PRODUCT NAME] in three lengths: Short (50 words): For product cards Medium (150 words): For category pages Long (300 words): For product detail page Key features: [FEATURE 1], [FEATURE 2], [FEATURE 3] Maintain technical credibility while being accessible to golfers of all levels.

Social Media

Weekly Social BatchClaude
Create a week of social content promoting [PRODUCT/CAMPAIGN]. For each day: Instagram (Feed): Caption (150-200 chars), 5 hashtags, visual description Instagram (Story): Short text overlay, poll or interactive element Twitter/X: Tweet under 280 characters LinkedIn: Professional angle (100-150 words) Day 1: Teaser | Day 2: Launch | Day 3: Tech spotlight Day 4: Social proof | Day 5: UGC prompt | Day 6: Data | Day 7: CTA

Strengths & Weaknesses - What works, where are gaps? 4. Implications for TaylorMade - Opportunities, responses Include sources for all claims.

Implementation

Getting your team up and running with AI tools

30-Day Rollout Plan

1
Week 1: Foundation
Confirm access for all team members. Create Claude Projects for brand voice and key product lines. Upload brand guidelines and style samples.
2
Week 2: Training
Team training session on each tool's capabilities. Share this guide. Practice with low-stakes content (social posts, internal drafts).
3
Week 3: Integration
Begin using for real deliverables with human review. Document successful prompts and approaches. Identify which tools work best for which tasks.
4
Week 4: Optimization
Review usage and identify additional opportunities. Refine Project setups and Custom Styles. Create team prompt library for common tasks.

Best Practices

Do

  • Be specific: Include audience, tone, length, format in prompts
  • Iterate: First drafts are starting pointsâ€”refine through conversation
  • Use Projects: Set up Claude Projects for brand consistency
  • Match tool to task: Use the comparison guide to pick right tool
  • Always review: AI output requires human judgment before publishing

Don't

  • Publish without review: AI can hallucinate facts or miss brand nuances
  • Share confidential data: Be mindful of what you input
  • Expect perfection: AI accelerates work but doesn't replace expertise
  • Use one tool for everything: Each has strengthsâ€”use the full stack
Know the Boundaries

Knowledge cutoffs: Claude through early 2025, others vary. Use web search for current info. No real people: AI can't generate identifiable public figures. Fact-check everything: AI can confidently state incorrect information.
